local_schema.short_desc: Keyring to which passwords will be saved
local_schema.longdesc: The name of the keyring gksu should use. Usual values are "session", which saves the password for the session, and "default", which saves the password with no timeout.

local_schema.short_desc: Save password to gnome-keyring
local_schema.longdesc: gksu can save the password you type to the gnome-keyring so you'll not be asked everytime

local_schema.short_desc: Display information message when no password is needed
local_schema.longdesc: This option determines whether a message dialog will be displayed informing the user that the program is being run without the need of a password being asked for some reason.

local_schema.short_desc: Prompt for grabbing
local_schema.longdesc: This option will make gksu prompt the user if he wants to have the screen grabbed before entering the password. Notice that this only has an effect if force-grab is disabled.

local_schema.short_desc: Sudo mode
local_schema.longdesc: Whether sudo should be the default backend method. This method is otherwise accessed though the -S switch or by running 'gksudo' instead of 'gksu'.

local_schema.short_desc: Force keyboard and mouse grab
local_schema.longdesc: Grab keyboard and mouse even if -g has been passed as argument on the command line.

local_schema.short_desc: Disable keyboard and mouse grab
local_schema.longdesc: Whether the keyboard and mouse grabbing should be turned off. This will make it possible for other X applications to listen to keyboard input events, thus making it not possible to shield from malicious applications which may be running.
